Chapter 2 Defining the data

Population and Samples

  • Population→Sample→Individuals

    • 总体→样本→个体

  • Variable-变量

  • Parameter-参数

  • Statistic-统计量

Types of data

  • Categorical variables-分类变量

    • binary variables-two levels-二元变量

      • dead/alive

    • ordinal variables-有序变量

      • letter grades(A, B, C, D, E)

    • nominal variables-名称变量

      • blood type(O, A, B, AB)

  • Numerical variables-数值变量

    • continuous variables-连续变量

      • speed

    • discrete variables-离散变量

      • cases of a certain disease in a year

  • Derived/ transformed variables-派生变量

    • defined by a function or expression in terms of other variables
    • e.g. BMI

Descriptive Statistics

  • central tendency

    • mean-均值

      • X―=∑i=1nXin
      • sample mean x―
      • population mean μ

    • median-中位数

    • mode-众数

  • dispersion and variability

    1. range-间距

      • Xlargest−Xsmallest

    2. quartiles-分位数, five-number summaries

      • Min, Q1, Q2, Q3, Max

      • interquartile range(IQR)-四分位数间距

        • IQR=Q3−Q1

    3. standard deviation-标准差

      • sample standard deviation-样本标准差

        • S=∑in(xi−X―)2n−1
        • n-1，自由度

      • population standard dev-总体标准差 σ

      • 只看标准差无法判断离散程度（还要看均值）

    4. variance-方差

      • sample variance-样本方差

        • S2=∑in(xi−X―)2n−1
        • n-1，自由

      • population variance-总体方差 σ2

    5. Mean absolute deviation(M.A.D.)-平均绝对离均差

      • M.A.D.=1n∑i=1n|xi−x―|

    6. standard error-标准误

      • s.e.=Sn
      • 样本均值的方差，来源于抽样误差
      • indicates how closely the population mean is likely to be estimated by the sample mean.
      • error bar，作为条形图的bar，上下对称

    7. coefficient of variation-变异系数

      • cv=sx―×100

  • chebyshev-切比雪夫定律

    • Regardless of how the data are distributed, at least (1−1/k2) of the values will fall within k standard deviations of the mean (for k>1)

Displaying Data

  • Dot Plot-散点图

  • Frequency table-频数表

  • Bar chart-条形图

    • y轴是数量

  • Histogram-直方图

    • y轴是频率

  • Density plot-密度图

    • skewness-偏度

      • g1=m3m23/2=1n∑i=1n(xi−x―)3(1n∑i=1n(xi−x―)2)3/2

    • kurtosis-峰度

      • g2=m4m22−3

  • Boxplot-箱图

    • 从下往上分别是五个位点
    • outliers的判定：Q3+1.5IQR作为上下界
    • box和bar的含义

  • Violin plot-小提琴图

    • 对称
    • 也可以不对称

Chapter 3 Data distribution and sampling

The normal distribution

  • AKA. Gaussian distribution

  • PDF of the normal distribution

  • 68-95-99.7 Rule

    • (μ−σ,μ+σ) contains 68% of the data.
    • (μ−2σ,μ+2σ) contains 95% of the data.
    • (μ−3σ,μ+3σ) contains 99.7% of the data.

  • convert any normal distribution to the standard normal distribution

    • Z=X−μσ
    • f(Z)=12πe−12(Z)2

  • Z-table: gives the cumulative probability up to the value z, which is P(Z<z)

  • Many statistics needs the data to be normally distribution

    • t-test
    • ANOVA
    • linear regression

  • How to know whether my data is normally distributed?

    • Does it appear bell shaped?
    • compute mean, median, mode
    • try 68-95-99.7 rule
    • run tests of normality (such as Kolmogorov-Smirnov)

  • 中心极限定理

    • 设从均值为 μ 、方差为 σ2 (有限)的任意一个总体中抽取样本量为 n 的样本，当 n 充分大时，样本均值的抽样分布近似服从均值为 μ 、方差为 σ2/n 的正态分布

  • Random sample

  • Statistics vs. Parameters

    • Statistics: calculated from data (e.g. sample mean)
    • Parameter: the true value in the entire population (e.g. population mean)

Chapter 4 Hypothesis Testing

  • If we want to estimate a parameter...

    • point estimate: x― is the best point estimate of μ
    • interval estimate: the parameter lies in a range with a probability (confidence level)

Confidence interval

  • Construct a confidence interval about μ with σ known

    • (x―−zα/2σn,x―+zα/2σn)

  • Construct a confidence interval about μ with σ unknown

    • (x―−zα/2sn,x―+zα/2sn)
    • Assumption: n≥30

  • Construct a confidence interval about μ with σ unknown and n is small

    • (x―−tα/2sn,x―+tα/2sn)

  • the width of the confidence interval is based on...

    • confidence level
    • variance
    • sample size

Hypothesis testing

  • Basic steps

    1. Assume H0

    2. State type of test and confidence level

    3. Determine and calculate appropriate test statistic

    4. Calculate p-value

      • p-value: the probability of your data or something more extreme under the null hypothesis
      • Math theory
      • Computer simulation

    5. Reject or not reject H0

    6. Write conclusion

Error and power

  • Type I error rate

    • α or p-value
    • 拒绝了正确的假设 (H0) 的概率

  • Type II error rate

    • β
    • 接受了错误的假设 (H0) 的概率

  • Statistical power

    • power=1−β

    • Factors affecting power

      1. size of the effect ⬆️
      2. standard dev ⬇️
      3. sample size ⬆️
      4. significance level ⬇️

    • formula

      • Zpower=differences.e.(difference)−Zα/2

      • n=2×σ2(Zβ+Zα/2)2difference2

        • Zβ: the desired power (Z0.8=0.84)
        • Zα/2: the desired significance level (Z0.025=1.96)

      • n=2×p―(1−p―)(Zβ+Zα/2)2(p1−p2)2

        • p―(1−p―): a measure of variability
        • p1−p2: effect size

Chapter 5 One-sample Tests of Hypothesis

Z-test single population mean

  • Hypothesis testing is designed to detect significant differences: differences that did not occur by random chance

  • In the “one sample” case: we compare a random sample (from a large group) to a population.

  • We compare a sample statistic to a population parameter to see if there is a significant difference.

  • H0: There is no significant difference between the sample mean and the population parameter. (μ=x)

  • Basic steps

    1. Assume H0

    2. State type of test and confidence level

    3. Determine and calculate appropriate test statistic

      • σ known: Z=X―−μσ/n
      • σ unknown, n≥100: Z=X―−μs/n

    4. Calculate p-value

    5. Reject or not reject H0

      • two-tailed rejection region: z≥zα/2 or z≤−zα/2

    6. Write conclusion

Z-test sample proportions

  • z=p^−p0p0(1−p0)n

    • p^: proportion observed

One sample t-test

  • use it when n is small, usually less than 100
  • t-distribution is flatter than z-distribution, but when n ⬆️, t-curve resembles z-curve
  • t=X―−μS/n (it is n)
  • df=n−1

Chapter 6 Hypothesis Testing: Two-sample inference

Paired t-test

  • H0: No difference between the two group (δ=0)

  • t=d―−δsd/n

    • sd: the standard dev of difference d

  • df=n−1

Unpaired t-test

  • Equal variance

    • t=(x―1−x―2)−(μ1−μ2)sp1n1+1n2

      • sp2=(n1−1)s12+(n2−1)s22n1+n2−2

    • df=n1+n2−2

  • Unequal variance

    • t=(x―1−x―2)−(μ1−μ2)s12n1+s22n2
    • df=v

Wilcoxon Rank Sum test

  • Nonparametric

  • Pros:

    1. Used With All Scales
    2. Easier to Compute
    3. Make Fewer Assumptions
    4. Need Not Involve Population Parameters
    5. Results May Be as Exact as Parametric Procedures

  • Cons:

    1. May Waste Information
    2. Tables Not Widely Available

  • H0: Both samples come from the same underlying distribution

  • Select the rank sum from the smallest sample as T

  • if TL<T<TU , do not reject H0

Wilcoxon Signed Rank Test

  • Assumption:

    • Paired
    • Random
    • Continuous

  • Steps:

    1. Obtain Di=X1i−S2i
    2. Make |Di| , ignore Di=0
    3. Assign ranks Ri , smallest with 1
    4. Sum '+' ranks and '-' ranks
    5. Choose T=min(|T−|,|T+|)

  • if T<Tcrit , reject H0

Chapter 7 Comparison of serveral groups: ANOVA

One-way ANOVA

  • Assumption

    • 正态分布
    • 方差齐性
    • 组间独立

  • H0:μ1=μ2=μ3 (There is no difference among group means)

  • F分布

    • σbetween2σwithin2∼Fn,m
    • 如果组间方差大（有差异），则F值大

  • ANOVA table

    • n: total sample size
    • k: the number of groups
    • Fk−1,n−k=MSBMSW=SSB/(k−1)SSW/(n−k)
    • SSB=∑j=1knj(xj―−x――)2
    • SSW=∑j=1n(nj−1)sj2
    • if Fcalculated>F0.05,k−1,n−k , reject H0

Correction for multiple comparisons

  • Bonferroni correction (n denotes the number of tests)

    1. set α=αoriginal/n
    2. pcorrection=poriginal∗n

  • Benjamini-Hochberg (FDR)

    1. put p-value from smallest to largest
    2. give them ranks i
    3. pFDR=p∗n/i

  • Fisher's LSD

    • t=X1―−X2―MSerror(1n1+1n2)

Two-way ANOVA

  • If there is two factor: A and B, then SST=SSA+SSB+SSE

  • H0: There is no difference in ... for factor A.

  • H0: There is no difference in ... for factor B.

  • H0: There is no interaction effect between factor A and B.

  • Two-way ANOVA table

    • a: the level of factor A

    • b: the level of factor B

    • r: the number of replicates

    • SS

      • SScells=∑∑r(X―ij−X――)2
      • SSA=br∑i=1a(Xi―−X――)2
      • SSB=ar∑j=ba(Xj―−X――)2
      • SSAB=SScells−SSA−SSB
      • SSE=∑i=1a∑j=1b[∑k=1r(Xijk−X―ij)2]

    • if Fcalculated>F0.05,a−1/b−1/(a−1)(b−1),n−ab , reject H0

Kruskal-Wallis test

  • Non-parametric, use it when:

    • data not normally distributed
    • variances are markedly different
    • data are measurements on an ordinal scale (e.g. ratings)

  • H0:

  • H=H∗=12N(N+1)×∑i=1kRi2ni−3(N+1)

    • N: the total number of samples
    • Ri: the rank total for each group
    • ni: the number of samples in each group

Chapter 8 Analysis of categorical outcomes: Chi-square test

Chi-square distribution

  • 非对称
  • 分布的形状与自由度k有关
  • k越大，分布越对称
  • 值非负

Chi-square test

  1. 拟合优度检验 (Chi-square test for goodness of fit)

    • 检验我们的分布和理论分布是否相同

  2. 独立性检验 (Chi-square test for independence)

    • 检验数据的两个变量之间是否独立

Chi-square test for goodness of fit

  • H0: There is no significant difference between the observed and expected values

  • χ2=∑(Oi−Ei)2Ei

    • Oi: the observed counts of category i
    • Ei: the expected counts of an category i
    • k: the number of categories
    • n: the number of independent trials of an experiment
    • df: number of groups - 1

  • if χcalculated2>χα2 , reject H0

  • Note

    • all Ei≥1
    • 不能有超过20%的Ei<5

Chi-square test for independence

  • H0: The two variables are independent

  • χ2=∑(Oi−Ei)2Ei

    • Ei=pi∗n
    • df=(rows−1)∗(columns−1)

  • if χcalculated2>χα2 , reject H0

  • Yates’s continuity correction

    • χ2=∑(|Oi−Ei|−0.5)2Ei

Chapter 9 Linear Correlation and Regression

  • covariance

    • cov(x,y)=∑(xi−X―)(yi−Y―)n−1

      • if cov(x,y)>0 , X and Y are positively correlated

Pearson’s Correlation

  • Assumptions

    • absence of outliers
    • normality of variables
    • linearity
    • Homoscedasticity (方差齐性)

  • H0:r=0

  • r=cov(x,y)var(x)var(y)

    • Between -1 and 1

    • Also calculated by r=SSxySSxSSy

    • The coefficient follows a T-distribution

      • t=r/1−r2n−2
      • df=n−2
      • if tcalculated>t0.05,df , reject H0

  • The pearson corrletion will be close to 1 only when the relationship is perfectly linear

Spearman rank correlation

  • H0:ρ=0

  • ρ(rs)=1−6∑di2n3−n

    • t=rsn−21−rs2
    • df=n−2

  • As long as the relationship is monotonous, the Spearman correlation will approach to 1

Linear Regression

  • Regression analysis is used to predict the value of one variable (the dependent variable, Y, 因变量) on the basis of other variables (the independent variables, X, 自变量)

  • Assumption

    • The relationship between X and Y is linear
    • Y is distributed normally at each value of X
    • The variance of Y at every value of X is the same (homogeneity of variances)
    • The observations are independent

  • The model is y=β0+β1x+ϵ

    • ϵ: Noise

  • H0: There is no linear relationship.

  • Least square line y=b1x+b0

    • b1=SxySx2

    • b0=y―−b1x―

    • To measure the strength of the relationship

      • R2=Sxy2Sx2Sy2=(r)2
